<br />
The relevant discussion at hand: The Wii fails as a game machine, because it doesn&#39;t put out actual good games that people want to play. I feel you&#39;d be on my side in this one, considering you listed every upcoming Wii game you wanted to play, and that list included only Smash Bros and Mario Kart. <br><BR><font size=1>08:57 12-03-2007</font></TD></TR><TR><td width='4' bgcolor=#FFFFFF>&nbsp;</td><TD ALIGN='LEFT' valign='top' width='70' bgcolor=#FFFFFF><font class="bfont"><B>Ken B</B></font></td><Td valign='top' bgcolor='#FFFFFF' ><font class="bfont">I was going to write a lengthy description of how a shortage does NOT benefit a company (hint: it&#39;s something they teach you in first-year college economics courses)--how such a "boost" to demand due to artificially constrained supply can only be sustained over a very, very short term--<br />
<br />
But then I saw an article on MSN today that spells it out much better.<br />
<br />
<br />
<a href=http://blogs.moneycentral.msn.com/topstocks/archive/2007/12/03/nintendo-shortage-wii-lly-hurts-company.aspx?GT1=10623>Shortages are BAD for companies, period</a><br />
<br />
<br />
To summarize:  You don&#39;t hope to sell 500k when you could be selling 700k.  Even if that meant by "artificially" constraining supply you could theoretically boost &#39;projected demand&#39; by 10%...you&#39;re still selling 500k.<br />
<br />
<br />
Nintendo is pumping out 1.8 million Wiis per month.  Based on how Nintendo had fared in the previous two generations that is an insanely high number.  There is no way to project an explosion in demand like that, even if you are gung-ho over your new product.  No person who values their job is going to say, "Yeah, I know we were dead last in the past decade, but let&#39;s make 5 million Wiis a month anyway."<br />
<br />
<br />
People go to stores to buy Wiis and get frustrated when there aren&#39;t any.  They don&#39;t go, "Gee, it&#39;s not here, damn now I wish I had TWO of them."<br />
